Functions, exit codes, and set-dash-e-u-o-pipefail.

Functions let you group commands and give them a name, and then call them just like a command. You define one with a name, parentheses, and curly braces. Inside, use the local keyword for any variable you don't want leaking out into the rest of the script; without local, every variable is global, which is a classic source of subtle bugs. Inside a function, dollar-one, dollar-at, and dollar-hash refer to the function's own arguments, not the script's. And a function returns the exit code of its last command, so a one-liner like is-root, which just runs a bracket-bracket test, works perfectly as a condition. If you need to return early, use the return keyword; do not use exit inside a function, because exit would terminate the entire script.

That brings us to exit codes generally. Every command signals success or failure with an exit code: zero for success, non-zero for failure. You read the previous command's code from the special variable dollar-question-mark. And you set your own script's exit code with exit, then a number; exit zero for success, exit one for a generic failure.

Now the centerpiece of writing robust scripts: the line set-dash-e-u-o-pipefail. By default, bash is remarkably forgiving. A command can fail and the script just carries on. An unset variable quietly expands to nothing. And a failing stage in the middle of a pipeline gets swallowed. For a throwaway script that's fine, but for anything that matters, you want the opposite: fail fast, and fail loud. So you put set-dash-e-u-o-pipefail right at the top. Dash-e exits the moment any command fails, so your script doesn't blunder on after a failed copy. Dash-u turns referencing an unset variable into an error, which catches typos like dollar-capital-Path when you meant dollar-capital-PATH. And dash-o pipefail makes a pipeline fail if any stage fails, not just the final one.

Two last tips. If you genuinely want to let a command fail without killing the script, check it explicitly with if-bang, "if not this command, then handle it." And when a script misbehaves, run it with bash dash-x, which prints every command as it executes, with all the variables expanded. That, plus a trap on the ERR signal to report the failing line number, is the fastest way to see what a script is really doing.
